==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sully
<hw>Sul"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sullied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sullying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sulien</ets>, AS. <ets>sylian</ets>, fr. <ets>sol</ets> mire; akin
to G. <ets>suhle</ets> mire, <ets>sich</ets>, <ets>s⟦uum⟧hlen</ets> to
wallow, Sw. <ets>s⟦oum⟧la</ets> to bemire, Dan. <ets>s⟦oum⟧le</ets>,
Goth. bi<ets>saulijan</ets> to defile.]</ety> <def>To soil; to dirty; to
spot; to tarnish; to stain; to darken; -- used literally and
figuratively; <as>as, to <ex>sully</ex> a sword; to <ex>sully</ex> a
person's reputation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Statues <qex>sullied</qex> yet with sacrilegious smoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No spots to <qex>sully</qex> the brightness of this solemnity.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sully</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sully
<hw>Sul"ly</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become soiled or
tarnished.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Silvering will <qex>sully</qex> and canker more than gilding.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sully</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sully
<hw>Sul"ly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Sullies</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>Soil; tarnish; stain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A noble and triumphant merit breaks through little spots and
<qex>sullies</qex> in his reputation.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sulphacid</ent>⟦br⟧
